I noticed a bug when scaling a node that have a StaticSprite2D component.
The bounding box have wrong offset on Y axis.

```
Node@ groundNode = scene_.CreateChild("Ground");
groundNode.position = Vector3(0.0f, -3.0f, 0.0f);
groundNode.scale = Vector3(200.0f, 1.0f, 0.0f);
Sprite2D@ boxSprite = cache.GetResource("Sprite2D", "Urho2D/Box.png");
StaticSprite2D@ groundSprite = groundNode.CreateComponent("StaticSprite2D");
groundSprite.sprite = boxSprite;
```

groundNode.scale cause this strange behaviour because the sprite isn't centered correctly.
Trying a manual hotspot I find right coords are not (0.5, 0.5) but something like (0.5155, 0.5155)

What's worng?

Historically the fixed GL pipeline had the `glEnable(GL_TEXTURE_2D)` function to control whether texturing is enabled or not. In core OpenGL 3.0, in Open GL ES 2.0 and in WebGL 1.0 and newer, this no longer exists.

Looking at the `Graphics::SetTexture()` code, there are the following

```
if (!gl3Support)
    glDisable(textureTypes_[index]);
```

and

```
if (!gl3Support)
    glEnable(glType);
```

which are run unconditionally on OpenGL ES 2 and WebGL 1. These don't propose any problems, but looking at the logs, they do generate a noisy GL error about `GL_TEXTURE_2D` being an unrecognized cap enum. Perhaps those should be gated under `#if !defined(__EMSCRIPTEN__) && !defined(GL_ES_VERSION_2_0)` or something equivalent?

The C function `gettimeofday()` is troublesome in JavaScript since it needs to resort to the function `Date.now()`. That function only has millisecond precision, and it is not optimized for high performance tasks, so there is a asm.js <-> non-asm.js boundary transition which impacts performance.

It is difficult to optimize `gettimeofday()` in Emscripten side, since we must return the current time of day, and can't return an arbitrary wallclock time. High-precision timers don't actually care about the time of day, so in Emscripten, for fastest and most precise high performance wallclock timing, it is advisable to use the `double emscripten_get_now();` function, which returns a wallclock time in milliseconds  with submillisecond precision. It is practically a call to https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Performance/now .

Therefore the implementation of `HiresTimer::GetUSec()` could be

```
#ifdef __EMSCRIPTEN__ // +
#include <emscripten/emscripten.h> // +
#endif // +

long long HiresTimer::GetUSec(bool reset)
{
    long long currentTime;

#ifdef WIN32
    if (supported)
    {
        LARGE_INTEGER counter;
        QueryPerformanceCounter(&counter);
        currentTime = counter.QuadPart;
    }
    else
        currentTime = timeGetTime();
#elif defined(__EMSCRIPTEN__) // +
    currentTime = (long long)(emscripten_get_now() * 1000.0); // +
#else
    struct timeval time;
    gettimeofday(&time, NULL);
    currentTime = time.tv_sec * 1000000LL + time.tv_usec;
#endif

    long long elapsedTime = currentTime - startTime_;

    // Correct for possible weirdness with changing internal frequency
    if (elapsedTime < 0)
        elapsedTime = 0;

    if (reset)
        startTime_ = currentTime;

    return (elapsedTime * 1000000LL) / frequency;
}
```

lines marked with (+) were added.

As a sidenote, I see that the file Timer.cpp actually repeats the implementation of obtaining a wallclock time five times almost identically in the following functions

```
unsigned Time::GetSystemTime()
unsigned Timer::GetMSec(bool reset)
void Timer::Reset()
long long HiresTimer::GetUSec(bool reset)
void HiresTimer::Reset()
```

which each call to `gettimeofday()`. The note to use the Emscripten-specific `emscripten_get_now()` instead of `gettimeofday()` would apply to each of these, since none of the functions seem like they need the actual time of day.

Window derives from BorderImage, but currently BorderImage methods and properties are not exposed to Window AngelScript API.

I've tried to do this in UIAPI.cpp, but to no avail:

``` angelscript
static void RegisterWindow(asIScriptEngine* engine)
{
    RegisterBorderImage<Window>(engine, "Window"); //=========
    RegisterWindow<Window>(engine, "Window");
}
```
